      <hedline>
        <hl1>Extra Credit: The Great American Civics Lesson; A Country of Laws</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wade Stone letter holds Leon E Panetta (Nov 14 Op-Ed) is wrong in calling for Vice Pres Al Gore and Gov George W Bush to come to an agreement about election, contending this is a nation of laws</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Time for a Bush-Gore Summit,'' by Leon E. Panetta (Op-Ed, Nov. 14):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Time for a Bush-Gore Summit,'' by Leon E. Panetta (Op-Ed, Nov. 14):</p>
        <p>Mr. Panetta and others call for the two candidates to come to an agreement because it would be the right thing for the country. This presumes that the country is best served by avoiding litigation to arrive at a president-elect. This presumption is wrong for three reasons:</p>
        <p>*This is a country of laws, and due process must be served to the fullest extent, especially in these critical circumstances.</p>
        <p>*There is no hard evidence that the country is enduring undue stress because of the situation. On the contrary, most people seem to be interested in a civic-minded way.</p>
        <p>*Precedent is being set, and a full legal resolution will help establish legal procedures and popular expectations should similar circumstances arise in future elections.</p>
        <p>WADE STONE  Florham Park, N.J., Nov. 14, 2000</p>
      </block>
